Run on a Linux/Jupyter environment
==================================

Install the build dependencies first. In a conda/mamba environment this is
usually enough:

    mamba install -c conda-forge root make gxx_linux-64 gfortran_linux-64 python

Check that the tools are visible:

    root-config --version
    g++ --version
    gfortran --version
    make --version

Build the UrQMD ROOT wrapper:

    make

If the build fails because old object files or libraries are incompatible with
the Jupyter container, force a fresh Linux rebuild:

    make rebuild-local

Run one local test job:

    make local-run

This creates/uses r_urqmd and writes an Event_*.root file there.

Run many local jobs without Condor:

    # NUM is the number of independent jobs, JOBS is parallelism.
    make local-parallel NUM=16 JOBS=16

After local jobs finish, gather ROOT files into ./roots:

    bash pull_data.sh

For a quick smoke test, reduce the event count in urqmd.cc before building.
Look for:

    const int event_num = (int) 500;

For example, change 500 to 10, then run make local-run.


Old RCF/Condor workflow
=======================

run this code at rcf:

1. make

# variable "NUM" at line 2 of conf.mk 
# is number of jobs decided to generate.
# Change this number before run "make clone"
2. make clone

# submit jobs
# The script queue_daemon is run in background.
# It automactically submit jobs.
# The maximum jobs run at same time can be tuned by qnum at line 4 of queue_daemon
3. nohup ./queue_daemon > log &

#when all jobs are done or one think it is time to kill jobs that are still running.
#use `ps` to check the progress id of queue_daemon then `kill the_id`
#try `condor_rm user_name` if want to kill jobs still running
#pull out urqmd root file from job folders by `bash pull_data.sh`
